title: Harbour 

You reach the old harbour.

A delivery drone circles above the water, searching for the best angle for a selfie.  

In the hinterland, a dust storm is brewing, its grit already scratching at your throat.

On the quay, a vendor leans against his dented water tank, hoisting a cloudy glass and calling out:

Vendor: One sip for a coin. Or you keep walking thirsty. 

- #harbour

@vendor_scene  
title: Approach the vendor  
max-visits: 1
tags: harbour

You walk over to the tank. Faded posters hang from it, half covered in dust. 

You can still make out the headlines: 

Headline1: Harvests in the region down 70%. 

Headline2: Blackouts hit the outskirts. 

Headline3: The polycrisis is gaining momentum. 

- #vendor

@pay_vendor  
title: Buy water
max-visits: 1
tags: vendor

You hand over some crypto. The water tastes metallic, but it eases the scratching in your throat. 

The vendor cleans some glasses.  

- #vendor

@ask_policrisis  
title: What does "polycrisis" mean?
tags: vendor
max-visits: 1

Me: Sorry, what exactly is a polycrisis? 

The vendor raises his eyebrows and gestures towards the harbour with his chin. 

Vendor: It used to be simple: first you had a power outtage, then maybe some protests. One after the other. 

He counts them off on his fingers. 

Vendor: Now the fields burn while the water is scarce, while prices shoot up, while people flee. And each of these things makes the others worse. 

He shrugs. 

Vendor: That's what they call a polycrisis. Many crises at once, feeding each other. 

For a moment he looks at you, weighing you up.  

Then he leans back against the tank.   

- #vendor

@ask_direction 
title: Ask for the teahouse
on-arrival: know-way = 1 
tags: vendor

Me: Can you tell me how to get to the teahouse?

Vendor: Follow the water until you reach the long pier with the small lighthouse at the end. You'll recognize the teahouse by the paper lanterns. They leave them out even in a storm. 

You thank him, follow his gaze along the water and set off. 

Between crates and moored boats, a child draws with a stick in the dust. 

- #quay

@child_drawing
title: Go closer
view-if: know-way = 1 
tags: quay

It's only a few lines, but you immediately recognize a small church, a school building, a rocket.

For a moment the wind holds its breath. 

Then a gust sweeps through the harbour and smears the lines until only grey dust remains. 

The child glances at the empty spot, sets the stick down again and starts drawing anew. 

- @way_teahouse

